            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Heather Sharma\u2019s story is one written on the streets of San Francisco, not in a boardroom. Raised in the dry heat of Bakersfield, her world was one of practicality. Her father was a mechanic, her mother a bookkeeper, and the future they envisioned for Heather was simple: a steady job, a local boy, a quiet life. For years, she followed that path, working retail and waitressing jobs after graduating high school, feeling a vague but persistent sense of being out of place.\n\nThe turning point came at 22 when she met Sameer Sharma, a charming software engineering intern from the Bay Area visiting family. For Heather, he represented a different world\u2014one of ambition, diverse cultures, and coastal fog. Swept up in a whirlwind romance, she moved to San Francisco with him, married, and embraced her new life and name. For a decade, she supported his burgeoning tech career, managing their small Potrero Hill apartment while he worked long hours. But as his world expanded, theirs contracted, and they grew apart under the pressure of divergent paths.\n\nThe divorce at 33 left Heather unmoored in one of the world's most expensive cities. She had no degree and a spotty resume. Refusing to return to Bakersfield defeated, she sought stability. She saw a hiring sign for Muni operators\u2014a union job with good pay and benefits that didn't require a college education. It was her lifeline. She passed the rigorous training, her calm demeanor a perfect fit for navigating the city\u2019s chaotic streets.\n\nNow 40, Heather is a veteran operator, a familiar face on the 38 Geary line. She lives in a rent-controlled one-bedroom in the Inner Richmond, a short bus ride from her depot. Her daily routine is dictated by her shift schedule, but she finds comfort in its rhythm. Her colleagues are her family, a blunt, funny, and fiercely loyal crew. She kept the name Sharma, a quiet testament to the journey that brought her here. Her dreams are no longer grand or romantic; she hopes to save enough for a down payment on a small condo, perhaps in a quieter East Bay town. More than anything, Heather cherishes her independence, earned mile by mile, piloting her 40-foot coach through the city that she finally, truly, calls her own."
