        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers that first week, age 22. She stood on the Potrero Hill balcony, watching the fog devour the skyline. Sameer, smelling of ambition and new laundry, held her from behind. He promised her the world, and she believed him because this city felt like the whole world. The cold air was a shock, a thrill. It was the moment she traded her own quiet path for his glittering one, a decision that would define the next decade of her life.\n\n2.\nIt was a company party at a sleek SoMa venue, around age 30. Heather stood alone by the vast windows, holding a cocktail while Sameer was swarmed by colleagues speaking a language of acronyms and IPOs. He looked so at home, so vibrant. She saw a gulf open between them right there on the polished concrete floor. For the first time, she felt more out of place in his world than she ever had in Bakersfield. It wasn\u2019t loneliness; it was the quiet, chilling sting of irrelevance.\n\n3.\nAt 33, a month after Sameer moved out, she was walking down Geary, the divorce papers heavy in her purse. The thought of calling her mom, of admitting defeat, was suffocating. Then she saw it: a banner on a bus depot. \u201cNow Hiring Operators. Good Pay. Benefits.\u201d It wasn't glamorous. It was real. It was a lifeline she could grab herself. In that instant, the vague idea of going \u201chome\u201d died. She chose the city instead, deciding she would be the one driving.\n\n4.\nAbout a year into the job, age 35. A chaotic scene erupted at Geary and 19th\u2014an argument, a spilled bag, shouting. In her old life, she would have shrunk. But behind the wheel of the 38R, she felt a preternatural calm. She keyed the mic, called Central, and de-escalated the situation with a firm, steady voice that surprised even herself. As she pulled away from the curb, she felt a surge of pure ownership. This competence was hers, earned block by painstaking block.\n\n5.\nJust last week, on her day off. She sat at a window seat at Cinderella Bakery, sipping coffee and watching a 38-Geary bus rumble past. She knew the operator\u2019s shift schedule. She recognized the specific groan of that coach\u2019s brakes. A quiet smile touched her lips. This wasn't the life she was promised on a foggy balcony years ago, but it was the one she had built for herself. A simple apartment, a steady paycheck, and an entire city unfolding outside her window\u2014a map she finally knew by heart."
